Yes, but that is also why this problem will not go away, and why the reasonable lose these arguments. If the twitter person acted in a more mentally healthy manner, then we would already not have this problem, because she would not project her entire personality on a drawing of a sleep paralysis demon. And because it matters less to us, a redesign of the character, which is what she demands, also matters less to us. Kind of like with Morgan, I suppose. She has just about as many distinctive looks as she has artists who have drawn her, but we all recognize her as Morgan, because despite not even having any stories Morgan already has an identity built up that goes beyond any single depiction of her.

As strange as it is, I can understand the complaint if I look at the mindset. It's not something I agree with, I loathe how the artist takes the typical Twitter route in dealing with it (don't harass this guy, she says, while basically asking people to harass him), and I support not giving in to disempower this mindset. But for the design itself, I don't really care that much because the character goes beyond that. And maybe Missy could actually be a little more interesting from a visual design perspective. I already support different artists giving their own interpretations of characters, and always have.

I think the best answer is to never involve yourself with this flavor of twitter crazy in the first place. Yet it's something that can happen with any author here, because many of us will simply use art when posting we think comes close to the characters in a story in question, or authors will be inspired by art they see online. Case in point, all the stories with previously established characters.
